"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>现在，也许杰森只是从他自己的经济角度进行了过度推断——<a href="https://twitter.com/zachcoelius/status/1715800756333453823">科技初创公司正在遭受苦难</a>，因为他们在 2022 年经济崩溃之前筹集的现金已经耗尽且无法替代。但事实上，现在很多美国人都在对经济发表非常负面的言论。尽管有所有经济好消息，但消费者信心<a href="https://twitter.com/crampell/status/1717904753047319030">仍然低迷</a>。 </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg" width="1318" height="450" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:450,&quot;width&quot;:1318,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:85922,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F29c582fe-d05c-415c-b9da-377d0ded400a_1318x450.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>人们无数次地试图解释这种消极情绪，但我认为其中很大一部分只是党派情绪的表达——或者，正如孩子们所说的，“共鸣”。有大量数据显示，美国人倾向于认为国民经济比他们自己的个人财务状况差得多。凯文<a href="https://jabberwocking.com/americans-dont-think-the-economy-is-bad-republicans-do/">·德鲁姆 (Kevin Drum) 有一些证据表明</a>，这种国家与个人的分裂主要是由共和党人推动的： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg" width="1267" height="626" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/da101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:626,&quot;width&quot;:1267,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:94901,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fda101951-847a-4325-bc80-07a2d49611e4_1267x626.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：昆尼皮亚克大学，作者<a href="https://jabberwocking.com/americans-dont-think-the-economy-is-bad-republicans-do/">：Kevin Drum</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>因此，共和党对国家现状的不满似乎才是造成这里大部分负面情绪的真正原因。如果非要我猜的话，我想说 2020 年夏天的记忆可能笼罩在共和党人对国家局势的看法上，让他们感觉国家正在以一种他们从未有过的感觉来反对他们。</p><h4> 2.中国正在建设军事装备。美国则不然。</h4><p><a href="https://twitter.com/tshugart3/status/1716259376183361842">美国国防部的一份新报告</a>显示了中国军力建设的速度有多快。</p><p> （首先，不要告诉我美国在国防上的支出比中国多得多，因为这不是事实；中国将大部分军费开支<a href="https://www.aei.org/op-eds/chinas-real-military-budget-is-far-bigger-than-it-looks/">记在账外</a>，而且因为<a href="https://cepr.org/voxeu/columns/debating-defence-budgets-why-military-purchasing-power-parity-matters">他们的钱更划算</a>……。事实上，两国的军费开支可能<a href="https://twitter.com/MEaglen/status/1689283338102616065">大致相等</a>。）</p><p>以下是国防分析师 Tom Shugart 对国防部报告的<a href="https://twitter.com/tshugart3/status/1716259376183361842">详细分析</a>（<a href="https://twitter.com/tshugart3/status/1716465378635751757">这是第二部分</a>）。基本上，中国正在建造大量的船舶、飞机和导弹。这些是它将在<a href="https://twitter.com/ianellisjones/status/1718701969093558549">台湾或南中国海战争</a>中用来对抗美国的武器。它还正在建造更多的核武器。</p><p> Shugart 主题的一些摘录：</p><blockquote><p> [中华人民共和国通过增强解放军的军事能力，正在对该地区的邻国采取更多的胁迫行动（只要问问菲律宾和台湾就知道了）。在提高对抗美国的能力的同时，它似乎基本上不再有兴趣谈论了……</p><p>报告称，今年解放军海军的舰体数量从 340 艘增加到 370 艘，水面战斗舰艇数量从 125 艘增加到 140 艘……30 艘舰体数量的增加超出了我的预期，水面战斗舰数量也增加了 15 艘。我知道他们正在建设，但不知道他们建设得那么快……</p><p>就解放军未来的增长而言，国防部预计到 2025 年将拥有 395 艘舰艇，到 2030 年将达到 435 艘……国防部估计解放军去年已建造了 21 艘元级潜艇，而 2022 年为 17 艘……</p><p>转向解放军空军：今年的报告显示，解放军空军目前拥有 1900 架第四代战斗机中的 1300 架（我假设 1300 架也包括第五代战斗机），比上一年增加*500*……</p><p>报告显示，中国远程导弹的各个类别都有大幅增长。部署的洲际弹道导弹发射器从 300 个跃升至 500 个，导弹数量从 300 个增加到 350 个……虽然发射器数量保持不变，但中程导弹（即“关岛杀手”）的数量估计却增加了从有点模糊的“250+”到可靠的500……</p><p>美国国防部目前估计中国拥有 500 枚核弹头库存，比去年增加了 100 枚。它还将更长的时间表提前至 2030 年“拥有超过 1,000 枚弹头”，而到 2036 年将拥有“约 1,500 枚”弹头。</p></blockquote><p>这绝对是惊人的军事建设速度，而且还不是战时。这远远超出了美国所能控制的范围。中国每年建造21艘潜艇，而美国则难以建造<em>两艘</em>。这是<a href="https://www.defensenews.com/naval/2022/01/03/us-navy-avoided-a-2022-trough-in-submarine-fleet-size-but-industry-challenges-threaten-future-growth/">去年的</a>：</p><blockquote><p>即将卸任的特朗普政府随后提出了 72 至 78 艘攻击潜艇的目标，而拜登政府此后<a href="https://sgp.fas.org/crs/weapons/RL32665.pdf">确定了 66 至 72 艘攻击潜艇的范围</a>——除非有什么改变，否则对海军来说仍然遥不可及……</p><p>该工业基地由主承包商通用动力电船公司和支持造船商亨廷顿英格尔斯工业公司的纽波特纽斯造船厂领导，一直难以按计划每年交付两艘弗吉尼亚级攻击潜艇。两个船厂各自建造船只的不同部分，然后轮流由谁进行最后的组装和交付。承包商迟迟将一艘又一艘的船交付给海军。</p></blockquote><p>美国国防工业基地已萎缩至 20 世纪 90 年代的一小部分。军事分析家帕特里克·福克斯<a href="https://twitter.com/RealCynicalFox/status/1717223315662627033">有这样的说法</a>：</p><blockquote><p>拜登政府最明显的失败之一是他们拒绝积极进行再工业化以提高我们的武器制造能力。这种必要性在 2022 年变得更加明显，并且在此期间变得更加重要。</p></blockquote><p>他还展示了更多数据，说明我们为乌克兰制造炮弹付出了多少努力——这只是我们为与中国发生冲突而需要建造的炮弹的一小部分。</p><p>如果你不担心这个，你应该担心。你可以安慰自己，美国的技术仍然比中国好一点（也许），但世界大战告诉我们，如果你的技术相当好，数量上的巨大优势是决定性的。美国现在正处于这种不对称的失败者一方。这个世界上不再有民主的武库，这个事实应该让你感到困扰。</p><h4> 3.产业政策实际上并不是为了低工资</h4><p>在过去的几个月里，出现了很多对产业政策<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-pushback-against-industrial-policy">草率的批评</a>，我很快就会在另一篇文章中讨论更多这些批评。但也有一些有趣且明智的批评，我觉得我也应该解决这些问题。例如，<a href="https://www.slowboring.com/p/the-industrial-policy-dilemma">马特·伊格莱西亚斯认为</a>，产业政策将难以创造良好的就业机会，因为它依赖廉价工资作为国际竞争力的来源：</p><blockquote><p>假设你是一个贫穷的国家......然后有人受到你国家低工资的诱惑，建造了几家工厂......现在作为一个持续的事情，他的利润率非常高，因为工资太低了。工厂的工人不喜欢这样，开始谈论……罢工，要求加薪。政府做什么？……如果政府关心产业政策和创建一个发展型国家，它可能<a href="https://pseudoerasmus.com/2017/10/02/ijd/">会选择镇压劳工并帮助镇压罢工</a>。</p><p>为什么？嗯，因为即使工厂工人的工资过低……国家经济发展的整个战略都是建立在利用这一事实的基础上的……你要做的就是吸引更多的投资，建造更多的工厂，并将更多的工人从农场转移到工业工作中。部门重新分配……是提高工资的策略……</p><p>发展型国家的首选举措是比自由市场<em>更加敌视工人利益</em>……对于像美国这样已经富裕的国家来说，困境在于很难想象一个富裕国家如何才能获得通过保持低工资来变得更富有……[D]你想制定自己的<em>产业政策</em>——抑制工资——以防止外国竞争者偷走你的行业吗？</p></blockquote><p>这种批评值得认真对待，因为毫无疑问，过高的工资将使美国工业在国际市场上失去竞争力。由于美国经济规模庞大且<a href="https://data.worldbank.org/indicator/NE.EXP.GNFS.ZS">相对封闭</a>，美国人习惯于只考虑为国内市场生产。你可以通过关税等措施保护国内市场。</p><p>但事实上，为<em>世界</em>市场生产极其重要，不仅因为世界市场很大，而且因为为世界生产产品可以推动企业提高生产力水平。因此，在这里你必须具有竞争力，并且不要被中国的竞争严重低估。如果美国工人不断罢工并获得越来越高的工资，最终印度、巴西或德国将没有人愿意购买波音飞机、福特汽车或英特尔半导体；他们会从中国购买。</p><p>但从数量上来说，低劳动力成本有多重要？马特引用了<a href="https://pseudoerasmus.com/2017/10/02/ijd/">一些历史研究</a>作为证据，表明日本纺织工业在 20 世纪初通过保持较低的劳动力成本在竞争中击败了印度纺织工业。但有什么理由认为这个例子与美国当今的处境相关吗？</p><p>首先，当时的纺织制造业属于劳动密集型行业，这意味着在企业的成本计算中，劳动力成本显得尤为重要。 2020 年代的高科技制造业，例如半导体行业，是资本密集型产业——制造大量机床，然后为工厂配备知道如何操作这些工具的博士级员工。是的，你需要一些低技能工人来建立、清洁和守卫晶圆厂，并为博士人员提供午餐等。但这些人的工资不会占生产成本的很大一部分。你所面临的主要劳动力成本主要是你必须支付给超高技能工人的高薪；正如任何科技公司所知，这些工人并不倾向于组建工会并推动工资不断上涨。</p><p>我们特别应该看看中国做对了什么。中国不是全球高科技制造业的中心，因为劳动力成本低；事实上，它的劳动力<a href="https://www.logisticsmgmt.com/article/global_labor_rates_china_is_no_longer_a_low_cost_country">不再非常便宜</a>，而且多年来它<a href="https://www.conference-board.org/publications/China-Competitiveness-Rising-Labor-Unit-Costs">一直不被认为</a>是特别低成本的生产国。相反，中国的竞争基于规模——由于其密集的供应商网络和训练有素的生产工程师组成的庞大劳动力，中国是唯一一个可以快速生产大量高科技产品的地方。与此同时，德国的制造业工资甚至高于美国，并且是众所周知的高科技制造和出口强国。 </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg" width="777" height="572" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:572,&quot;width&quot;:777,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:80009,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6822b6d9-523f-46f5-85fe-a657be172d88_777x572.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源： <a href="https://www.logisticsmgmt.com/article/global_labor_rates_china_is_no_longer_a_low_cost_country">物流管理</a>，2023 年 1 月</figcaption></figure></div><p>因此，马特认为过高的工资<em>可能会</em>破坏产业政策，这在形式上是正确的，但尚不清楚这在现实生活中有多重要。马特将产业政策与工资抑制等同起来当然是不正确的。</p><p>我<em>确实</em>同意马特的观点，他指出了降低土地和监管成本等非工资成本的重要性。但我认为他的批评缺少的是对生产力的考虑。对于竞争力来说，重要的不是劳动力成本或土地成本或其他任何东西，而是“ <a href="https://www.bls.gov/k12/productivity-101/content/what-is-productivity/what-is-unit-labor-cost.htm">单位劳动力成本</a>”——每单位产出的生产成本是多少。公司的生产力越高，其单位劳动力成本就越低，即使其工资确实很高。</p><p>当然，降低土地和监管审批成本是降低单位劳动力成本的重要途径。但改进技术和<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/american-workers-need-lots-and-lots">鼓励自动化也很关键</a>。在产业政策方面，我们应该考虑的真正权衡不是“工资与竞争力”，而是“工厂创造就业机会与竞争力”。产业政策倡导者不需要接受低工资；他们需要接受低工资。他们需要承认，制造业通过促进当地服务的<a href="https://eml.berkeley.edu/~moretti/multipliers.pdf">乘数效应</a>间接创造了良好的就业机会。</p><h4> 4.太阳能利好消息</h4><p>太阳能是您的朋友。它并不是一种比煤炭或核能更软弱、更不男子气概的能源形式。这不是破坏资本主义的嬉皮士阴谋。这并不是一个绝望的后退，让我们靠豆荚生活并吃虫子。这是<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/dont-be-a-decel">一场真正的技术革命</a>，是人类的聪明才智利用太空聚变能并将其直接转化为纯电力的现代奇迹。</p><p> More importantly, it&#39;s just really really cheap. Jenny Chase, an analyst at Bloomberg New Energy Finance, has <a href="https://twitter.com/solar_chase/status/1718296328676032934">a great annual thread</a> where she assesses the situation of the solar industry. Here are a few choice tidbits from this year&#39;s thread.</p><p> A lot of people used to claim that we need a technological breakthrough in solar cell efficiency in order to make solar economically viable. This was never true — it turned out we only needed cost reductions — but in any case, we did keep increasing cell efficiency incrementally, and those increases added up. Chase writes:</p><blockquote><p> Incremental improvements in solar modules continue. 2023 was the move from PERC (module efficiency ~21.3%) being the standard design, to TOPCon (~22.3%). The average solar module in 2023 was about 21.6% efficient, up from 15.4% (a now-obsolete multicrystalline design) in 2012.</p></blockquote><p> That&#39;s a pretty big increase!</p><p> Anyway, speaking of the cost declines, they just keep on happening. In 2021 there was a sudden small increase in solar costs, causing some people to think that the era of learning curves was over. But it was just a temporary bump from temporarily higher materials costs in the wake of the pandemic. Chase notes that costs have come back down:</p><blockquote><p> In October 2021, when the standard mono module price was 27.3 US cents per W, I said it would &quot;come back down over 1-2 years&quot; (referring to all-time low of 19 cents in summer 2020). Since it&#39;s now 13.6 US cents in normal markets (ie not the US or India), not too bad a call.</p></blockquote><p> As for whether levelized cost of energy (LCOE) is a good measure of costs, Chase drily notes that it&#39;s pretty much the only measure of cost that matters to utilities on the margin:</p><blockquote><p> By the way, LCOE is just a fancy way of saying &quot;the price you gotta pay someone for power to get them to build a power plant&quot;.</p></blockquote><p> Of course, if you keep building lots and lots of solar, eventually intermittency starts to matter more. Chase explains that this intermittency will manifest as low or even negative electricity prices during the sunniest parts of the day:</p><blockquote><p> After grid and land issues, the next big challenge for PV will be power price cannibalization. Basically, solar plants in one area all generate at the same time. This means that they reduce the price of power at that time, “cannibalizing” their own revenues…High solar penetration resulting in power price cannibalization also affects other power plants, but not as much as it affects solar, because solar plants generate most at times when solar is pushing the price down most. This will inhibit further solar build…By 2030 most countries will have spot power prices of zero for a few hours every sunny day.</p></blockquote><p> Intermittency doesn&#39;t really matter when you only build a modest amount of solar. But when you build an absolutely huge amount, like we&#39;re expected to do in the near future, it starts to bite a lot. But Chase is optimistic that batteries are going to be a pretty effective solution to that problem:</p><blockquote><p> It may well be that &quot;negative power prices for a few hours every sunny day, followed by high evening power prices when the sun goes down&quot; is a problem solved by capitalism and batteries…Utility-scale batteries became a thing much faster than I expected. <a href="https://twitter.com/YayoiSekine">@YayoiSekine</a> &#39;s team recorded 16.8GW/32.9GWh of gross energy storage capacity additions worldwide in 2022, and expect 41.9GW/98.6GWh in 2023.</p></blockquote><p> Anti-solar people also claim that solar won&#39;t have enough land to build on. This is probably an issue for wind, but for solar, Chase thinks it&#39;s not that big of a deal:</p><blockquote><p> There is enough land for lots of solar. There are enough golf courses in the US for about 370GW, ffs. There&#39;s also loads and loads of roofs…</p></blockquote><p> So anyway, that&#39;s all very optimistic stuff, and you should be optimistic too! Solar, together with batteries, looks like the first major step-up transition we&#39;ve gotten in electric power generation technology since the advent of coal itself.</p><h4> 5. What&#39;s destroying the humanities?</h4><p> A bunch of people got upset when it was reported that the University of North Carolina system <a href="https://www.wunc.org/education/2023-10-19/unc-system-state-nc-budget-3-7-billion-2023">will now give out</a> distinguished professorships only to scholars in STEM fields, and not to professors in the humanities. Some <a href="https://twitter.com/RebeccaSpang/status/1717887249679777940">took it as a sign</a> of the “dismantling of public higher ed in the USA”. I&#39;m not so sure it means that much, but I do think it&#39;s very likely that the shift away from an emphasis on the humanities will continue. The reason is that undergrads just don&#39;t want to major in these subjects anymore: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg" width="1304" height="806" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:806,&quot;width&quot;:1304,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:154887,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe46f7fc9-c160-4b1a-81fa-06db1123fbab_1304x806.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#FFFFFF" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2"><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://twitter.com/benmschmidt/status/1562212497272279041">Ben Schmidt</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> The hard, cold fact is that while professors tend to see themselves as scholars first and educators second, from a university&#39;s perspective, they are primarily <em>instructors</em> ; if there aren&#39;t as many students to instruct, fewer profs are needed.</p><p> Why are humanities majors (except for philosophy) in a state of collapse? My typical go-to explanation for this is economic — these degrees are less useful for getting a high-paying job, which is why we see students majoring in computer science, health, business, and other practical stuff more. And the timing lines up with the Great Recession, which strongly implies that once economic constraints started to bite, America&#39;s youth became less eager to take a four-year voyage of intellectual pleasure and more focused on grabbing the brass ring.</p><p> But Bates College prof Tyler Austin Harper <a href="https://twitter.com/Tyler_A_Harper/status/1717935971985924576">believes</a> that the humanities have shot themselves in the foot by being “nakedly ideological”. He writes:</p><blockquote><p> [W]e&#39;ve created the conditions for what&#39;s going on at UNC. How did anyone think we could get away with being nakedly ideological for years without any chickens coming home to roost?..Universities have always been tacitly left-leaning and faculty have always been openly so, but institutions have never been this transparently, officially political. Almost every single job ad in my field/related fields this year has some kind of brazenly politicized language…</p><p> An example. Here&#39;s language from a current lit job ad: &quot;We see this position as building on recent hiring in the English department in decolonial and anti-racist pedagogies and practices as well as a recent cluster hire in research related to diversity, equity, and inclusion.&quot;…Imagine if a public university job ad instead read: &quot;We see this position as building on recent hiring in the English department in traditionalist pedagogies and practices as well as a recent cluster hire in research related to pro-life ethics, nationalism, and family values.&quot;</p><p> …This is about universities shamelessly embracing, as their official institutional posture, an openly ideological framework/stance.</p></blockquote><p> Color me skeptical. While I do think that conservatives and red-state politicians are very mad at this ideological shift in humanities academia — and I agree with Harper that they have a right to be upset — I doubt that this is driving kids&#39; desire to avoid these majors. Young people are the ones who choose what to major in, not Republican politicians, and the young generation has a <em>lot</em> of lefties. I doubt very much that faculty job descriptions with “diversity, equity, and inclusion” in their names are what&#39;s making kids avoid history and English majors like the plague.</p><p> Instead, my guess is that the ideological shift in humanities academia is more an effect of the sector&#39;s shrinkage than the cause of it. As all the money and opportunity in humanities academia dries up, people who care about living a decent life and having a well-paying job drift away from the profession. Who does that leave in humanities departments? People who obsessively love their research, of course, but also committed ideologues. So those ideologues will have proportionately more and more sway over hiring and over the culture of the field as a whole.</p><p> Of course, humanities departments that become more ideological may be more likely to provoke conservative officials to cut their budgets more. But I think the collapse in humanities majors has to be regarded as the likeliest culprit for the shift here. So although I&#39;d personally like to see humanities departments be less ideological, I doubt this will save them from decline. The only thing that will save them, I predict, is if the US economy returns to a state in which young people are confident that they can get a good job no matter what they major in.</p><p> So basically, humanities profs who want to save their fields should be strong proponents of a pro-growth economic agenda. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>Subscribe now</span></a> </p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-ae2?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-ae2?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>Share</span></a></p> ; 
Does the notion of a "Global South" still make any sense?There are really four Global Souths. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/does-the-notion-of-a-global-south https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/does-the-notion-of-a-global-southNoah Smith Sun, 29 Oct 2023 04:03:02 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg" width="100%" height="auto" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:&quot;auto&quot;,&quot;width&quot;:&quot;100%&quot;,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:null,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:null,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2526fe3a-ad43-412f-9df1-5997312a9c1f_1292x680.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture><div></div></div></a><figcaption class="image-caption"> Map by <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?curid=139254470">Specialgst</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Israel-Gaza war has caused a lot of heated rhetoric to be thrown around. One of the big talking points is that the US&#39; support of Israel will cause it to <a href="https://twitter.com/ForeignPolicy/status/1715563624704483356">lose support among the nations of the “Global South”</a> . I don&#39;t know if that&#39;s true or not — Muslim countries seem likely to be at least annoyed with the US, but <a href="https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2023/10/25/pro-israel-rallies-allowed-in-india-but-palestine-solidarity-sees-crackdown">India seems</a> more on the pro-Israel side. But regardless, this has drawn my attention to the highly questionable way in which the categories “Global North” and “Global South” are used — not just in online discussions, but by official organizations like the United Nations.</p><p> A lot of people use “Global South” interchangeably with “developing countries”, since countries in the north of the globe tend to generally be richer than countries in the south. In fact, I used it myself, in a post about global development, back in 2021: </p><div class="digest-post-embed" data-attrs="{&quot;nodeId&quot;:&quot;e03a655e-2f43-4147-b77e-4f5b0f2cd1aa&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;The other day on Twitter we were discussing the &#8220;Global South&#8221; (because Brad DeLong had a podcast about it). So I thought I&#8217;d do a post checking in on the general status of developing countries, because there have been some interesting developments in recent years that might change our overall &#8230;&quot;,&quot;size&quot;:&quot;sm&quot;,&quot;isEditorNode&quot;:true,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Checking in on the Global South&quot;,&quot;publishedBylines&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:8243895,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Noah Smith&quot;,&quot;bio&quot;:&quot;Econ blogger&quot;,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/89fd964a-586f-461a-9f5a-ea4587d45728_397x441.png&quot;,&quot;is_guest&quot;:false,&quot;bestseller_tier&quot;:10000}],&quot;post_date&quot;:&quot;2021-03-15T08:26:59.495Z&quot;,&quot;cover_image&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd670ce83-4b78-4ac8-8db3-e8fab54fef54_1024x683.jpeg&quot;,&quot;cover_image_alt&quot;:null,&quot;canonical_url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/checking-in-on-the-global-south&quot;,&quot;section_name&quot;:null,&quot;id&quot;:33710182,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;newsletter&quot;,&quot;reaction_count&quot;:28,&quot;comment_count&quot;:27,&quot;publication_name&quot;:&quot;Noahpinion&quot;,&quot;publication_logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fbucketeer-e05bbc84-baa3-437e-9518-adb32be77984.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F04281755-2cd6-42e5-a496-e69153abebb2_281x281.png&quot;,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false}"></div><p> But as soon as you try to actually categorize all the countries of the world into two groups, you run into difficulties. For example, in 1980 <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandt_Report">the Brandt Report</a> , issued by an independent international commission, drew a nice clean line: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd2646870-8e89-478b-b495-a0a2c5777f3b_700x407.png" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd2646870-8e89-478b-b495-a0a2c5777f3b_700x407.png 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd2646870-8e89-478b-b495-a0a2c5777f3b_700x407.png 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd2646870-8e89-478b-b495-a0a2c5777f3b_700x407.png 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fd2646870-8e89-478b-